detect other objects through the use of spectrums and light
levels. It has several characteristics which can be used to
finely tune how and when an object can be seen.


SPECTRUMS

There are currently 4 spectrums in the new system:

Visible: The visible light spectrum. Acts pretty much as a
stand-in for the old light system.

Ultraviolet: Short wavelength light. This light is emitted
by both the sun and stars, and can be used to see at night.

Infrared: Long wavelength light. Emitted by living objects,
this can be used to see in the dark to a limited extent. The
living objects will be seen, as well as any exits, due to the
difference in temperature of air currents.

Sensory: Psionic sensing. Acts much like infrared.


ACTIVE/PASSIVE VISION

Most creatures use passive vision, meaning that they are 
dependent on an exterior source for the light needed to
see. For example, the sun provides reflected light to see
in the visible spectrum; living objects and air currents
provide for difference in ambient temperature to see in
the infrared spectrum.

Active vision describes sight by emission; in other words,
the creature that is doing the observing actually has some
means of emitting light, serving as its own emission source.

Races: Currently races are set up as follows:

Elf, Daemon: active ultraviolet.

Dwarf, gnome, halfing: passive infrared.

All living creatures emit in the infrared and sensory
spectrums.

Garou are capable of seeing active UV and passive IR when
in Crinos or Wolf form.



INVISIBILITY, HIDING, ABSORPTION

Invisibility in a spectrum is either on or off. Invisible 
items can be seen by an observer in two ways: 
  1) By being able to observe the object in a spectrum other
     than that which the object is invisible in.
  2) By having the ability to see invisible objects in a
     spectrum by some means other than vision: magic, etc.

Objects may also set a hiding, or camoflage, level. This is
compared to the observers (int + wis)/2 when deciding if the
object is visible or not.

Finally, objects may have a level of absorption, meaning that
they absorb (or fail to reflect) a certain amount of light
that is cast on them. If there is not sufficient ambient
light, an object may be invisible by virtue of it simply
being too dark. Imagine trying to see a brown cloak in a
dimly lit room.

Note: Objects with shorts of 0, and objects which return
  a number greater than the level of the observer from the
  query_invis() function are also considered invisible. This
  supports the old method of invisibility (wiz invis).


MECHANICS

The light system is based on a range of 0 to 100 for all
light levels.

To determine if an object or its surroundings may be seen,
several checks are performed for each spectrum.

1) If the object is invisible in the spectrum being checked,
   and the observer is not capable of seeing invisible
   objects in that spectrum, the object is considered
   invisible in that spectrum.
2) Next, the light level of the environment of the object
   is calculated for that spectrum.  If the observer has
   active vision in the spectrum, the active vision level
   is added to the ambient light. Next, if the object has
   an absorption level for that spectrum, that level is
   subtracted from the ambient light. 
3) If the viewer has passive vision, the spectrum is 
   infrared, and the object is an emission source, then the
   ambient light for purposes of viewing the object is
   considered to be the maximum of the ambient light or the
   standard emission level (currently defined as 50).

4) If the result is > 0, the object is considered visible in
   that spectrum.

Seeing environments is a little different in that if the
spectrum is a detailed spectrum (visible, ultraviolet, and
sensory), then objects, long descs, and exits can be seen.
If the spectrum is not detailed, then only objects, short
descs, and exits may be seen. Detailed means capable of
distinguishing fine details.

Note: when the code is finished, outside rooms will use the
ambient light emitted by the sun, moons, and stars as 
determined by the astronomy daemon and the room's terrain
type, i.e. a forest will gain less light from the moon
than will an open road.



The following attributes can be set by level for each
spectrum (see add_visibility_level() for details) :

Interior light: The ambient light inside a container. This
  is how rooms can have light inside them. This light is
  added to the light of any objects within the container
  which are also emanating light.

Emanating light: The light given off by an object, like a
  torch or the like. The difference between this and interior
  light is subtle: interior light is cast into an object, 
  emanated light is cast into the environment of the object.
  An object can emit light into itself, its environment, or
  both at the same time.

Absorption: The amount of light NOT reflected by an object.
  The higher the absorption, the brighter the ambient (or
  interior) light of the environment needed to see the
  object.

Camoflage: The amount of hiding being performed by an object.
  This really isn't a light level property, but refers more
  to the ability of the object to blend into its surroundings.
  This can be done by spectrum as well, as an object might
  have a great camoflage in the visible spectrum that looks
  like a riotous combination of bright orange and purple in
  the ultraviolet spectrum.

Active vision: The amount of light emitted by an observer to
  see its surroundings. This light does NOT benefit any other
  observers in the same environment. Liken it to attempting
  to see via someone elses tight-beamed flashlight: they will
  never seem to hold the light where you want to look.


The following attributes can be set either on or off only by
spectrum (see set_visibility_flag() for details):

Opacity: Whether or not a container passes exterior light to
  its interior, and vice versa.

Passive/active vision: Whether an observer is capable of seeing
  in a particular spectrum, either actively or passively.

Emitter: Whether or not the object emits in the spectrum, for
  purposes of detection with passive vision.

Invisible: The invisibility of an object in the spectrum.

See invisible: Whether or not an observer is capable of
  detecting invisible objects in the spectrum.



NITTY-GRITTY

All constants are defined in /secure/include/spectrum.h.

Objects must inherit INH_VISIBILITY (defined in mudlib.h) in
order to be either light sources, observers, or hidden/invisible.

The functions used to test for visibility are defined in simul_efun,
and are available to all objects:

--------------------------------------------------------------------
varargs int visible_to(object oItem, object oObserver, object oEnv);

Tests if an object (oItem) is visible to an observer (oObserver) in
a particular environment(oEnv). oEnv is optional, and if not
provided it defaults to the environment of oItem.

Returns an integer containing the following bits:
  VIS_IS_ACTIVE - observer used active vision to see the object.
  VIS_IS_PASSIVE - observer used passive vision to see the object.
  VIS_IS_DETAILED - observer saw the object in a detailed spectrum.
  VIS_IS_AURA - observer saw the object in a non-detailed spectrum.
  VIS_IS_INVISIBLE - object was invisible in the spectrum, but was
                     seen anyways.



--------------------------------------------------------------------
varargs int environment_visible(object oObserver, object oEnv);

Tests if an environment is visible to an observer. If oEnv is 
not provided, it defaults to the environment of the observer.

Returns an integer containing the following bits:
  VIS_IS_ACTIVE - observer used active vision to see.
  VIS_IS_PASSIVE - observer used passive vision to see.
  VIS_IS_DETAILED - observer saw in a detailed spectrum.
  VIS_IS_AURA - observer saw in a non-detailed spectrum.



--------------------------------------------------------------------
varargs mixed *visible(string sItem, object oEnv);

Tests for the existence of a visible object matching the
string, much as present() works.

Returns a two-element array consisting of:
  1) the object, if found. 0 otherwise.
  2) the bits from visible_to().

Example: ({ object_that_was_found, VIS_ACTIVE })



--------------------------------------------------------------------
object *visible_inventory(object oContainer, object oObserver);

Returns a list of the objects within a container that
are visible to an observer.

Returns an array of 2 element arrays as defined for 
visible().



--------------------------------------------------------------------
varargs void show_object_list(mixed *axTuples, object oObserver);

Prints a nice inventory listing, taking into account color,
numbers of items, etc.

This is called by show_inventory, but may be used if needed.
axTuples is an array of object/bit pairs as defined by visible().



--------------------------------------------------------------------
varargs void show_inventory(object oEnv, object oObserver);

Prints an inventory listing for an environment for an observer.

This should be used for all inventory lists.


--------------------------------------------------------------------




The functions defined on objects which implement light are in
/inherits/visibility.c (INH_VISIBILITY):

--------------------------------------------------------------------
int query_visibility_level(int iType, int iSpec);

Returns the level for a particular category by spectrum.

Categories (iType) as defined in spectrum.h are:
  VIS_INTERIOR: interior light for the object
  VIS_ABSORPTION: amount of light the object absorbs
  VIS_EMANATION: amount of light the object emits
  VIS_HIDDEN: camoflage level of the object
  VIS_ACTIVE: active light ability of the object

Spectrums as defined in spectrum.h are:
  SPCT_VISIBLE
  SPCT_INFRARED
  SPCT_SENSORY
  SPCT_ULTRAVIOLET
  SPCT_SONIC (not used currently)

Returns an int.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
varargs mixed *query_visibility_levels();

Returns all the visibility levels in an array.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
int query_visibility_flag();

Returns the visibility flags in a single int. The individual bits
should be queried using the following macros as defined in spectrum.h:
  VIS_GET_FLAG(flags, spectrum, flag);


--------------------------------------------------------------------
void set_visibility_flag(int iSpectrum, int iFlag);

Sets a visibility flag on an object.

Ex. this_object()->set_visibility_flag(SPCT_INFRARED, VIS_PASSIVE_VISION);


--------------------------------------------------------------------
void clear_visibility_flag(int iSpectrum, int iFlag);

Clears a visibility flag on an object.



--------------------------------------------------------------------
int add_visibility_level(int iType, int iSpectrum, int iAdd);

Adds to a visibility level for an object.

Ex. this_object()->add_visibility_level(VIS_EMANATION, SPCT_VISIBLE, 1);
    is the equivalent of set_light(1) for an object.

Ex. this_object()->add_visibility_level(VIS_INTERIOR, SPCT_VISIBLE, 1);
    is the equivalent of set_light(1) for a room.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
int recursive_interior_light(int iSpec);

Calculates the total interior light for a container for a spectrum.
